{% block content %}
<div class="container">
  <h1>Overview</h1>

  <p>Welcome to the Open Multilingual Wordnet (OMW) project.  The goal is to
it easy to use wordnets in multiple languages. The individual wordnets
have been made by many different projects and vary greatly in size and
accuracy. We are working to make a shared format and link the wordnets
together.  OMW and its components are
      <a href='http://opendefinition.org/'>open</a>: they can be freely used, 
      modified, and shared by anyone for any purpose.  
      There is a fuller list of wordnets at the Global Wordnet Association's
      <a href='http://globalwordnet.org/wordnets-in-the-world/'>Wordnets
	in the World page</a>.

    <p>If you use these wordnets, please cite the original projects
    who created them, if you got value from this
    aggregation/normalization, please cite <a href="#Bond:Paik:2012">Bond and Paik (2012)</a>.


      <ul>
	<li> OMW Version 2.0, the current (experimental) version, uses the Collaborative Interlingual Index to link the wordnets together.
	  <ul>
	    <li>Python Wn library
	    <li>OMW Data
	  </ul>
	<li> OMW Version 1.1 added automatically created wordnets for over a 150 languages  from <a href='https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Wiktionary:Main_Page'>Wiktionary</a>
    and the <a href='http://cldr.unicode.org/'>â€ŽUnicode Common Locale
    Data Repository</a>  (<a href='https://aclanthology.org/P13-1133/'>Bond and Foster, 2013</a>). 

	<li> OMW Version 1.0 linked wordnets to Princeton WordNet 3.0
	using a simplified structure.  We (i) extracted and normalized
	the data, (ii) linked it to v3.0, (iii) put it in one place,
	(iv) made a simple web interface and (v) integrated into NLTK.
      </ul>
    
</div>
